Crimea and Sudetenland, same fight?
BRUSSELS – Russia's takeover of Crimea constitutes the most serious example of peacetime aggression that Europe has experienced since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly today customary to minimize the importance of the "lessons of Munich" when referring to this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier conceded to Hitler's demands regarding Czechoslovakia in order to appease the Führer.
Nevertheless, if the Western world were to close its eyes to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, after the takeover of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might deeply regret their inaction.
Within Western capitals, reactions have thus far proved mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – an expulsion from the G8, for example – might seem laughable if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the worst catastrophe of modern times, the man tirelessly striving to revive a fallen Russian empire.
If the West is to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination shown by Putin.
The numerous successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialist project have so far cost him almost nothing.
His initiative in favor of the Eurasian Economic Community has allowed Russia to bring together a number of resource-rich states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here we have the most precious geostrategic trophy of all – Ukraine – which could well fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "ceases to be an empire," as explained by former U.S. National Security Advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the contrary, with a bribed and then subordinate Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the majority of Ukrainians have no desire whatsoever to join Putin's empire, it is very likely that the country led by the Russian president will now become a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union stripped of the Communist Party.
It is essential that the international community's response be commensurate with the degree of adventurism displayed by Putin.
Cancellations of summits, trade agreement proposals, and other participations in forums as unproductive as the G8 will not be enough.
Only actions involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions that could affect Russian citizens—who, let us remember, keep reelecting Putin to power—will allow us to hope to see the Kremlin leave its expansionist trajectory.
What kind of sanctions could they be?
First, Turkey could decide to close the Bosporus Strait to Russian transport, as it did after the Russo-Georgian War of 2008.
At that time, Turkey blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent the United States from intervening, although it now clearly appears that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial vessels heading to Russian ports in the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy – as well as on Putin's military claims – would be considerable.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Turkey could thus turn against Putin the motive he invoked to justify the annexation of Crimea – namely that he would protect the Russian ethnic groups living there – by asserting that it itself protects its Turkish cousins of Tatar ethnicity, who, given the poor treatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to turn back in mid-air in order to head to Kiev to support the new interim government.
The prime minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who, as Putin knows, is not exactly a softie, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transport – until Putin recalls all his troops from Crimea so that they return to their bases, namely those of Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good if Turkey could rely on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in the event that Russia sought to intimidate it.
Secondly, the American president Barack Obama could impose the same type of financial sanctions against Russia that he imposed on Iran regarding its nuclear program.
These sanctions indeed significantly undermined the Iranian economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the American financial system for all banks dealing with Russian banks or companies would allow for an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power is based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist course could cost them dearly.
Thirdly, Obama could remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
True drama in Putin's eyes, the disintegration of the Soviet Union constituted for China the most formidable geostrategic windfall one can imagine.
In an instant, this empire that had seized millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries, and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become important trade partners for China.
The Russian invasion of Georgia seriously upset China, as was evident during the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held after the war (this regional group bringing together a number of former Soviet states with common borders with China and the motherland).
Russia tried to get the SCO to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The Organization, however, expressed its disagreement.
However, the Central Asian member countries – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – would never have dared to oppose the Kremlin without China's support.
It is now up to Chinese President Xi Jinping, however, to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's boldness.
The true test of this Chinese claim to assert itself as a genuine and responsible protagonist within the international community will indeed take place very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this manifest violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of the territorial integrity of Ukraine?
Two other sanction options are also conceivable.
Each Russian leader could thus see their visas refused or canceled.
It would also be possible to freeze a certain number of assets, particularly those that have been laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
It is only when the pain becomes unbearable, and particularly for the elites, that this kind of struggle that Putin is currently conducting could fail.
The price of inaction could well turn out to be considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on this promise from America to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Furthermore, when Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the express condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) would guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one could blame Ukraine if it decided to renuclearize its defense (something it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous phrase, "You had a choice between war and dishonor.
You have chosen dishonor, and you will have war." Obama and other Western leaders are now faced with a similar choice.
If they were to choose dishonor, we can be certain that the bold Putin will eventually serve them a new war.
